  "local_port": 49468,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What can I do with an infant at Walt Disney World?",
  "response": "Walt Disney World can be a magical experience for visitors of all ages, including infants. Here are some tips and activities to make the most of your visit with a little one:\n\n1. **Baby Care Centers**: Each park has a Baby Care Center where you can change diapers, feed your baby, and take a break in a quiet, air-conditioned space. They are equipped with changing tables, high chairs, microwaves, and nursing rooms.\n\n2. **Rider Switch**: For attractions that may not be suitable for infants, you can use the Rider Switch program. One adult waits with the baby while the other rides, and then they switch without waiting in line again.\n\n3. **Gentle Rides**: Many rides are suitable for infants. Examples include \"It's a Small World,\" \"Peter Pan's Flight,\" \"Dumbo the Flying Elephant,\" and \"The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh.\" These rides are gentle and often have bright colors and engaging scenes that infants may enjoy.\n\n4. **Parades and Shows**: Infants can enjoy the sights and sounds of parades, fireworks, and shows. Make sure to find a spot where you can easily leave if the baby gets fussy.\n\n5. **Character Meet and Greets**: While infants may not fully understand the experience, meeting characters can make for memorable photos. Characters like Mickey Mouse, Minnie Mouse, and other Disney favorites can be very engaging and gentle with little ones.\n\n6. **Stroller Rentals**: If you don\u2019t want to bring your own stroller, you can rent one at the parks. A stroller can be very handy for navigating the large parks and giving your baby a place to rest.\n\n7. **Play Areas**: There are several play areas designed for young children. Examples include the Dumbo play area at Magic Kingdom and the splash zones in Epcot.\n\n8. **Nap Time**: Take advantage of quieter attractions like the Hall of Presidents or the Tomorrowland Transit Authority PeopleMover where your baby can rest or nap.\n\n9. **Dining**: Many restaurants are baby-friendly and provide high chairs. Buffets and family-style meals can be convenient as you can get food quickly without waiting for individual orders.\n\n10. **Pack Essentials**: Make sure to bring plenty of diapers, wipes, baby food, and any other necessities. Having these items handy will help avoid any stress during your visit.\n\n11. **Stay Hydrated and Cool**: Florida can be quite warm, so ensure your baby stays hydrated and cool. Hats, sunscreen, and lightweight clothing can help.\n\nBy planning ahead and knowing what to expect, you can create a magical and enjoyable experience for both you and your infant at Walt Disney World.",
